ks blood \n&gt; &gt; from one&#39;s soul. \n&gt; &gt; \n&gt; &gt; Seeing the world, people and ob=\r\njects as obstructions or temptations or \n&gt; &gt; &quot;leeches&quot; is silly. Being disg=\r\nusted with the world is as much an \n&gt; &gt; attachment (a negative attachment) =\r\nas is being fascinated with it! \n&gt; &gt; World and people can exist and act in =\r\nways that may be natural to \n&gt; &gt; them. Whatever they do, they are never the=\r\n problem or blockage for \n&gt; &gt; your own spiritual evolution. You may do vari=\r\nous actions and give \n&gt; &gt; various things to various people, based on kaarmi=\r\nk debts, and nothing \n&gt; &gt; you do is necessarily a bondage. Actions never bi=\r\nnd you, it is \n&gt; &gt; expectation of specific results from those actions that =\r\nbinds you. \n&gt; &gt; Give freely and magnanimously; and take whatever comes back=\r\n naturally, \n&gt; &gt; with no excitement and no regret. Remove ANY expectation t=\r\nhat may \n&gt; &gt; exist in your mind, from ANYONE, and become completely free. T=\r\nHAT is \n&gt; &gt; true sannyasa or renunciation, not seeing people as leeches tha=\r\nt cling \n&gt; &gt; on to you. \n&gt; &gt; \n&gt; &gt; If one becomes a sannyasin because one is=\r\n fed up with the world, it is \n&gt; &gt; probably a bad idea. When one discharges=\r\n most of one&#39;s duties and \n&gt; &gt; responsibilities to others, a sense of genui=\r\nne renunciation will \n&gt; &gt; naturally develop. If one runs away from the worl=\r\nd prematurely, Nature \n&gt; &gt; will drag one back later. \n&gt; &gt; \n&gt; &gt; *        *  =\r\n      * \n&gt; &gt; \n&gt; &gt; When Adi Shankara renounced, his mother was very sad. But=\r\n Adi Shankara \n&gt; &gt; did not see her as a leech. In fact, when she was on dea=\r\nthbed, he came \n&gt; &gt; all the way back and did her final rites himself, thoug=\r\nh that was \n&gt; &gt; completely against the traditional notions of sannyasa dhar=\r\nma. There \n&gt; &gt; is a big lesson in this. \n&gt; &gt; \n&gt; &gt; Actions and paying off yo=\r\nur debts do not bind you. In fact, inaction \n&gt; &gt; and pushing off a debt to =\r\nfuture MAY bind you! It is expectation in \n&gt; &gt; what you do and egoistic att=\r\nachment to what you do (feeling proud or \n&gt; &gt; ashamed) is what binds you. \n=\r\n&gt; &gt; \n&gt; &gt; *        *        * \n&gt; &gt; \n&gt; &gt;&gt; It is only when you take sannyasa t=\r\nhat they will leave \n&gt; &gt;&gt; you free. \n&gt; &gt; \n&gt; &gt; Even to a sannyasin, many peo=\r\nple may cling. They may come for \n&gt; &gt; knowledge or wisdom or to fulfil thei=\r\nr pride related to doing good \n&gt; &gt; religious work. So many people clung to =\r\nVivekananda and other monastic \n&gt; &gt; disciples of Ramakrishna. If one expect=\r\ns something back from such \n&gt; &gt; followers, well-wishers and disciples (e.g.=\r\n admiration, learning well, \n&gt; &gt; spreading knowledge or message in the worl=\r\nd, giving money for the \n&gt; &gt; religious order, etc), there is no difference =\r\nreally between wife and \n&gt; &gt; children and them. In other words, attachment =\r\ncan form and bind you. \n&gt; &gt; \n&gt; &gt; What binds you is your attitude towards pe=\r\nople and your expectations \n&gt; &gt; from people and NOT how much people like yo=\r\nu and how attached THEY are \n&gt; &gt; to you. To be free, you do not need people=\r\n to &quot;leave you free&quot;. You \n&gt; &gt; can be surrounded by thousands of people who=\r\n are attached to you \n&gt; &gt; heavily and yet you can be free. Their attachment=\r\n binds *them*. To be \n&gt; &gt; free, have no attachment and no expectations. Giv=\r\ne other whatever your \n&gt; &gt; body, mind and soul allow you to give. Have no e=\r\nxpctations of getting \n&gt; &gt; anythying back. Take whatever comes back by itse=\r\nlf. Simple! \n&gt; &gt; \n&gt; &gt; *        *        * \n&gt; &gt; \n&gt; &gt;&gt; When you fall sick You=\r\n will be tempted to go in for their help and \n&gt; &gt;&gt; vice versa. \n&gt; &gt; \n&gt; &gt; &quot;V=\r\nice versa&quot; is not a problem. Taking care of a sick person if one is \n&gt; &gt; ab=\r\nle to, whether it is wife or parents or children or someone else, is \n&gt; &gt; n=\r\not binding. If there is an expectation of a return favor, THEN it is \n&gt; &gt; b=\r\ninding. \n&gt; &gt; \n&gt; &gt; Regarding taking help: Expecting anything from anyone cau=\r\nses bondage, \n&gt; &gt; but taking what comes by itself, with neither excitement =\r\nnor regret, \n&gt; &gt; does not cause bondage. Ma Sarada nicely demonstrated this=\r\n once. \n&gt; &gt; \n&gt; &gt; When Swami Yogananda was badly sick, Ma Sarada asked his e=\r\nrstwhile \n&gt; &gt; wife (before sannyasa!) to come and serve him. That is so \n&gt; =\r\n&gt; unconventional! Swami Yogananda protested saying it will set a bad \n&gt; &gt; e=\r\nxample. But Swami Yogananda did not have any expectations and this \n&gt; &gt; was=\r\n done voluntarily by his wife (or under the instruction of Ma \n&gt; &gt; sarada, =\r\nbut not due to any expectations or pressure from Yogananda). \n&gt; &gt; After Yog=\r\nananda overcame his reservations, he was neither excited nor \n&gt; &gt; regretful=\r\n. He accepted the service equanomously and not worrying about \n&gt; &gt; what oth=\r\ners will think or say. \n&gt; &gt; \n&gt; &gt; In fact, if one puts pressure on oneself a=\r\nnd wants to prove to the \n&gt; &gt; world how good one&#39;s renunciation us, THAT ma=\r\ny be an attachment. \n&gt; &gt; &quot;Expecting&quot; the world to see one&#39;s renunciation an=\r\nd appreciate one (or \n&gt; &gt; not criticize one) is a very subtle attachment. M=\r\na Sarada may have \n&gt; &gt; detected a subtle attachment and put Swami Yogananda=\r\n in a spot \n&gt; &gt; intentionally and made him overcome the attachment. Great t=\r\neachers \n&gt; &gt; like Ramakrishna and Ma Sarada teach subtle and valuable lesso=\r\nns in a \n&gt; &gt; practical way. It may not even be obvious to onlookers that th=\r\nere was \n&gt; &gt; a lesson there! This is how sadgurus operate.. \n&gt; &gt; \n&gt; &gt; *    =\r\n    *        * \n&gt; &gt; \n&gt; &gt; Being able to renounce wife, children, parents, si=\r\nblings, house, car \n&gt; &gt; etc is a great thing. But, if one thinks that those=\r\n are &quot;all \n&gt; &gt; connections and ties&quot; that bind one, one is badly mistaken. =\r\nThose are \n&gt; &gt; the gross ones - the external ones. The biggest bondage is i=\r\nnternal. \n&gt; &gt; The identification with a body and identification with a subt=\r\nle \n&gt; &gt; individual identity (e.g. the notion that one is Narasimha, an \n&gt; &gt;=\r\n engineer, a scholar, an astrologer etc) are much stronger bondages \n&gt; &gt; th=\r\nan any others. \n&gt; &gt; \n&gt; &gt; If one&#39;s hands or legs are cut off or if a tiger i=\r\ns eating one alive \n&gt; &gt; or if one is suffering from a terrible disease, can=\r\n one focus the mind \n&gt; &gt; on god and not think of the body and its suffering=\r\n? If one thinks &quot;*I* \n&gt; &gt; am suffering&quot; and starts weeping, is one really f=\r\nree? \n&gt; &gt; \n&gt; &gt; If someone praises a sannyasin for his renunciation, devotio=\r\nn to god, \n&gt; &gt; wisdom or spiritual attainment, will no sannyasin feel even =\r\na little \n&gt; &gt; pride? If so, is one really free? \n&gt; &gt; \n&gt; &gt; If a sannayasin d=\r\noes sadhana and experiences some special things or \n&gt; &gt; gets some siddhis, =\r\nwill it not give a little bit of pride or \n&gt; &gt; satisfaction? If so, is one =\r\nreally free? \n&gt; &gt; \n&gt; &gt; Focusing so heavily on external renunciation and mak=\r\ning external \n&gt; &gt; objects of attachment seem like a major thing, while igno=\r\nring the real \n&gt; &gt; attachment inside one (the sense of &quot;this is I&quot; and &quot;the=\r\nse are mine&quot;), \n&gt; &gt; is like beating up a tiger cub and feeling proud of the=\r\n achievement, \n&gt; &gt; while ignoring the big tiget just lurking behind one and=\r\n waiting to \n&gt; &gt; pounce on one! \n&gt; &gt; \n&gt; &gt; *        *        * \n&gt; &gt; \n&gt; &gt; Let=\r\n me say one thing clearly. Sannyasa or external renunciation is an \n&gt; &gt; *at=\r\ntempt* to cut oneself off from a few external objects that cause \n&gt; &gt; tempt=\r\nation (and bondage!) internally. It is not a guarantee that \n&gt; &gt; internal t=\r\nemptations and bondages are completely destroyed. The real \n&gt; &gt; bondage com=\r\nes from the internal attachment and not from the external \n&gt; &gt; objects. Wor=\r\nk hard on removing it. Do not despise the external objects \n&gt; &gt; or see them=\r\n as &quot;leeches&quot; or become fed up with them. \n&gt; &gt; \n&gt; &gt; Best regards, \n&gt; &gt; Nara=\r\nsimha \n&gt; &gt; ---------------------------------------------------------- \n&gt; &gt; =\r\n   Free Jyotish Software, Free Jyotish Lessons, Jyotish Writings, \n&gt; &gt; &quot;Do =\r\nIt Yourself&quot; ritual manuals for short Homam and Pitri Tarpana: \n&gt; &gt; http://=\r\nwww.VedicAstrologer.org\n&gt; &gt;       Films that make a difference: http://Sara=\r\nswatiFilms.org\n&gt; &gt;       Spirituality: http://groups.yahoo.com/group/vedic-=\r\nwisdom\n&gt; &gt;    Jyotish writings: http://groups.yahoo.com/group/JyotishWritin=\r\ngs\n&gt; &gt;                       Twitter ID: @homam108 \n&gt; &gt; -------------------=\r\n--------------------------------------- \n&gt; &gt; \n&gt; &gt; On Fri, Jun 3, 2011 at 2:=\r\n00 PM, chaudhuri.krishnendu wrote: \n&gt; &gt; \n&gt; &gt;     Sannyasa has got its own g=\r\nlory and advantages! The freedom of a \n&gt; &gt; sannyasin can hardly be describe=\r\nd. Only a sannyasin can entirely cut \n&gt; &gt; off all connections and ties. Tho=\r\nugh you have colored your heart, \n&gt; &gt; still all members of your family will=\r\n cling to you like leeches till \n&gt; &gt; the end of your life. You cannot entir=\r\n